<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n08166i"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n08" href="#n08166i">N08 (VI.B.6)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n08all.htm#n08166i"> 166(i)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> ovum (rugby) / Webb Ellis took up ball / &amp; ran</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources"><b>By the Way <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> The Oval Ball</b> The International Rugby matches have raised the old question: &ldquo;Why is the <mark>Rugby ball oval</mark> and the ordinary football round?&rdquo; One theory is, that in the old days nobody was apparently able to make a seamed leather ball which was a perfect sphere. Another, and more likely, theory is that a game where hands are used would be too easy to be sporting with a round ball. There seems to be no authentic record of the rules which governed games of football before <mark>H. Webb-Ellis &ldquo;took the ball in his hands and ran with it.&rdquo;</mark> <small> <a name="FJ11feb24" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#FJ11feb24"><cite title="source">Freeman's Journal</cite></a> (11 February 1924) 8/5</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: The game of rugby originated in 1823 at the Rugby School in England when &lsquo;William <mark>Webb Ellis</mark> ... with fine disregard for the rules of football as played in his time, first took the ball in his arms and ran with it.&rsquo; (inscription on the gates of the school) [Vincent Deane.]</mm> </dd></dl>
